segments.text: Rick Gerlach, who is the executive assistant to Mayor McCann of Houston, Texas.
Rick is an alumnus of the Department of Urban and Regional Planning at Texas A&M and is exercising an important role with regard to the development and growth of Houston.
And in that regard, I would like to begin with a rundown of your personal
past and how you came to be in urban planning.
Okay.
I was raised in Abilene, Texas and my father was a Texas Aggie and so naturally I went to Texas A&M beginning to study law.
and decided that wasn't exactly what I needed to do.
And in taking several political science courses from Claude Davis, he put the bug in my ear about perhaps going into planning rather than law.
There were less planners than lawyers then, and that's basically sort of the way that that happened.
Rick, you graduated when?
I got my master's in 72.
OK. And upon receipt of your master's degree, you came to Houston.
Well, actually, I came to Houston my last semester of graduate school, because I was on that urban extension fellowship with the city department.
And which got a lot of jobs, by the way.
I'd strongly suggest that implementing something like that in the future because it places your students without much trouble if they have any snack.
At the end of my tenure at In Model Cities, I was asked to stay as environmental project planner in In Model City department under Michael McAnany.
OK.
Then you were an intern at that time, more or less.
At that time, yes.
And then when you joined the municipal corporation as a permanent, was it under civil service?
Yes, it was.
I think I graduated on a Saturday, and I was at work Monday on the payroll.
What was your salary at that time?
And what is it now?
And a car.
We can go over that in a hurry.
Moving right along.
Right along.
Yes, you know how to make your old props feel bad, don't you?
Come join us.
Okay, so then you joined the Municipal Corporation in which position?
I started out as a...
a project planner in the Model City department.

And the interesting thing about the Model City program, and it sort of switched me out of planning in the case of a planning director type, was that you actually planned the project and you had the money to fund it.
Directly from the feds.
Right, right from the feds.
And you knew if your idea was good or bad.
You didn't have to wait 40 years to see if this concept was any good.

know your rehab program busted or you fixed the houses you know it was very very immediate type of planning and uh that was the phone and i told her to grab these copies quick and uh that sort of took me out of out of the traditional city planner type mode of thinking and into more uh planning and
managing it too.
There was a time that I was project manager for all those projects too.
I was administrator and planner.
So it was very very rewarding and revealing and you got to see whether you were right or wrong real fast and you had direct interface of course with the residents that your projects were
were impacting upon because all of us, the planners and functional areas, had a task force of neighborhood residents that we had to meet with.
And they actually designed with us, we planned with them, the types of programs that they wanted.
And so it was very revealing.
Did you have much interface with the housing authority?
At that time, no.
We really didn't.
At that time, the housing authority hadn't built any new units in 20 years.
And they were, no, we really didn't.
Then from that position, you moved to what?
Well, let's see.
I stayed, I moved to a senior project planner spot, which didn't do anything except pay me more and give me an assistant.
And then that was 1974.

And Mayor-elect Hawthorne was trying to put together an office of the mayor, or a part of the office of the mayor that could sort of deal with overall policy development, which is sort of funny because I always thought policies are crude and never developed.
But anyway, we were working at that time with several...
people, Bob Schultz, I think it was with one of the big eight accounting firms, and Alan Ackman with the assistance group out of Silver Spring, Maryland, to work on this proposal.
And all of a sudden, HUD comes up with capacity building demonstration projects.
So my boss at that time, which was Mike McEnany, who was the manager of planning for all the cities, and myself and Alan Ackman of the assistance group got together and we wrote.

a proposal, which we got funded for a quarter of a million dollars to do capacity building, which was sort of a, as I understood it, and it may be wrong, but a forerunner of how cities can deal with community development programs.
So we set up what was then called the Policy Planning Division of the Mayor's Office.
Among the things we were trying to do was to develop an urban policy, if you will, which we

managed finally to do last year to do a capital improvement program which the city hadn't had ever and yes it's true now they had a program but it never put everything together and it never was approved officially by motion as policy it was never done 1974 was the first
the first real capital improvement program per se.
The Public Works Department has always had a program.
And it's a negotiated program with the council.
But as far as an official document with project numbers and everything by function and year and funds and everything like that, it was the most complete one.
It was the first one we'd ever done.
At any rate, we
Passed a 1974-75 CIP program, which was basically the tail end of the bond election.
And then went right to work on a 1976 through 78 capital improvement program, which was developed a lot like most cities develop their programs and goals and objectives and the whole nine yards.
It was a relatively straightforward plan.
You said the whole planning process?
Yes.
And again, it was much more sophisticated.
The first one was sort of a kit of parts approach, but the other one I felt very good about because we really did isolate cost by objectives and types of projects that went through such.
We've abandoned it now because nobody paid any attention to it.
We had no mechanism and still don't of accounting for cost by project because our accounting system isn't
up to sorting across funds at this time.
We are doing that now.
So we kind of blew that off this last time.
And that's getting off track, however.
Anyway, and so the policy planning division then changed names to planning coordination.
When was this?
Well, that was with the, when Hawthorne's didn't run and Mary McCann was elected.
In 19, oh Lord.
78, I guess.
Yeah, our division not only did the capital improvement program and the revenue sharing budget, but we also did the operating budget for 77 and 78.
When the mayor came in, he removed the budget function out of that office and into his office, into the mayor's office proper in a management services
group.
Yes, that was in 78.
And they removed the three people out of our office that were doing it.
So that sort of left us with, well, doing about half revenue sharing budget, and they're doing the other half.
No operating budget, coordination basically A95, which they still do.
Under a new name,
called Planning and Management Division.

Planning and Management Division basically now, and that was where I was up until August of this last year, was set up trying to do operational planning, which is certainly maybe jargon, but what it is is we're trying to improve the budget process to allow for a cost accrual by objective.
if you will, output measures, some way to account for it.
We've set up the accounting system, at least we're in the process right now of setting up the accounting system to do that.

So we'll have a traditional line item budget over here, a line category, and we'll have, however, on the other side, an operational plan, which basically takes your money and tells you what you're getting for it.
And aside here, Rick, is that...

As part of our core curriculum at Texas A&M, students are required to take a course in the principles of accounting, which coins them with the principles of how to set up books and keep track of funding, the revenues, and the expenditures, and so forth.
I'm not sure that personally I agree that this should be part of the required core curriculum for graduate planning students.
But you may be able to comment on that from your particular point of view.
No, I think the accounting for the money, as far as planning, you can hire somebody to do that.
Some course that would teach you how to budget, how to set up a performance budget, not account for it.
Accounting is past tense.
That's not what planning is about.
I would suggest that...
perhaps some of the city management courses might be if you're going to require something rather than accounting.
I don't see that at all.
Well, it's been a problem to me personally, and I just, as long as we're touching on that, I don't like that.
I wouldn't have taken that course.
Okay.
Okay, then you went from that into the next phase of your career.
Well, I was...
We operated in planning and management.
This is really confusing, changing the names.
Can't tell the players without a program.
We operated without a director.
And we criticized the feds.
Oh, really?
We operated without a director for almost a year.
It might have been a year and a half.
And basically, what we had were two managers.
And I managed the hardware side of the shop, and a woman managed the software side, the social service side, for almost a year.

And I was sort of an executive without portfolio for a long time, basically operating under what I got by with was because of my very strong association with the Department of Public Works in capital improvement program and revenue sharing.
And that's where, to this day, a lot of my stroke comes from.
If I really need help, I can always feel like I can go to those guys.
I've helped them out on some things.
And they've helped me out on some things.
Basically, they don't have a planning group, per se.
And I was sort of their planner.
And so if we had to fight a planning argument, I'd go up there with the public works strength behind me and make planning points for them.
And if I had problems internally, they would take care of me.
That's the system everyone criticizes, but it is in fact in place.
Okay, then from that you went on to...
Okay, well from there, which puts us at August of 1980, there was a vacancy created on the mayor's office staff.
as an executive assistant position, which is sort of like a deputy mayor, but nobody wants to admit it.
And the mayor saw fit to ask me if I wanted to do that.
And I said yes, yesterday, and made the move.
Well, when you made that move, you left civil service behind you.
Yes, I did.
At that point.
Yes, I did.
So now you're serving at the pleasure of the mayor.
Absolutely.
And you like that, too.
Yes, I do.
It makes you responsive.
Yes, it does.
It makes you a little more careful.

But what happened was from a position where I was doing a lot of just staff research and stuff like that, I've actually gotten to a point where I'm liaison with the city planning department, the real estate department, the purchasing department, management information systems department.
my old division of the mayor's office, which is planning and management.
Who did I leave out?
I always leave somebody out anyway.
But then there's some functional areas dealing with energy, environment, legislation in terms of our analysis between legal department, the mayor's office, planning and management.
We have a consortium, and I'm the mayor's liaison with that.
and trying to keep up with boards and commissions.
Oh, yes, and supposedly liaison with the Metropolitan Transit Authority in their dealings with the office of the mayor.
Sounds like a bundle to me.
Making me old.
What do you do in your spare time?
That's another subject.
Anyhow...

Now that you're in this position, Rick, I'd like to ask you some questions about your perception of the planning process as we in planning envision it, how it has worked since you have come to Houston, how it is working currently, and then later on how you think it may evolve in the immediate future.
Let's begin with your earliest firsthand knowledge of how the planning process, if there is a planning process at all in Houston, how it operates.
Clearly, we all know that Houston doesn't have zoning.
But there may be other things it doesn't have.
And there may be things that it does have to compensate for non-zoning.
And we'd like to know about it.
Because in terms of the history of planning in Texas,
Houston is an anomaly in this sense.
And it's the largest single city in the state.

And as such, even if anyone wanted to, we could not overlook Houston in terms of its growth, in terms of how it accommodates growth, and in terms of how it relates to the formal planning process as we might conceive it in a textbook.
Well, in terms of the non-zoning, I came out of planning school raving about zoning.
I'm not sure that the absence of zoning necessarily means there's an absence of planning or a planning process.
After doing three capital improvement programs for the city,
I would find that there's a hell of a lot of planning that's going on.
We're basing it on something.
I've found in most cities that the form outweighs the substance in most planning exercises.
The city of Dallas, for example, it seems to me that while they manage their resources

much better at least reading wise they do much better than we do they account for things to the nth degree I'm not real sure that any more thought goes into to their physical facilities planning for example which is what I basically do the city has grown so quickly and
the dynamics of having a second downtown in three years where there used to be a residential subdivision, for example.
I'm not convinced that zoning would prohibit anything that's happened in the city of Houston.
It might have slown it up.
It might have gotten people thrown in jail.
But I really don't think, I honestly don't think that this is any
I'm not going to say better or worse, but any different from any city that would be totally unconstrained in any kind of growth.
It might have directed the location of activities to different areas than has, in fact, occurred.
But you're saying that it would have happened regardless of zoning.
I think so.
If you do have some .
The thing about zoning,
that I miss, or I think that some of our citizens are missing, is it's not going to prohibit a Greenway crossing.
It's not going to prohibit a Northwest crossing.
It provides a forum for citizens to discuss what the hell's going on in their neighborhood and if they can do anything about it.
We do not have that here.
I mean, you can do it politically.
If a guy wants to put a service station up next to the chairman of Exxon's house, he's not going to do it.
But the little guy, a mom and pop junkyard comes up next to him, that's what we're hurting on, I think.
And the fact that, and I think everyone will admit that all our codes of ordinances are geared to new development.
And the city, being as young as it is, it's just now getting to the point of redevelopment in these areas.
And we have no control.
in my way of thinking, that we need to ensure that any redevelopment is done in an orderly manner.

And I think that's the problem that we've got, not particularly zoning, because I really don't think, I mean, even most cities have a transition zone or an office zone or something like that, and that's what you have in Montrose and the Heights, and that's happening anywhere.
But you do have those nuisances, if you will, that zoning might prohibit, but I'm not sure that it's worth
that.
And another thing is a citizen just won't stand for it.

We're not sure in the academic circles how much of this is due to the public press and in terms of the editorial positions that are taken by the press in the Houston area and how much of it seems to be the popular culture of the time and the trend and the thing to be in favor of or against or whatever.
I find it
not all that easy to accept that the average citizen in Houston would be necessarily opposed to zoning.

However, I think it's not an important point because zoning, we all agree as planners, has definite limitations, particularly planners who have lived and worked in Europe, where the concept of zoning originated

and where they've gone beyond it now in terms of what it seems to me that, you know, this is not my interview, it's yours, but I just wanted to throw out that I think that zoning in the United States has really become almost an aberration and has expanded into what I would refer to as homogenized districts of single functions throughout a metropolitan area wide

urbanized district and it's not right because it leads to incredible inconveniences and they've got over this in Europe and now they think in terms of three-dimensional zoning where you have multi-purpose buildings and we're getting into this now in some of the core areas where you have uses stratified by whether they're below ground at the sidewalk level and then
on up into various elevations above street level, which seems incredibly practical and attractive.
So the idea of zoning, I think we can let's go into growth management then in terms of the planning process for Houston.
Does Houston attempt to compensate for the lack of zoning in any way?
And if so, how does
How does this operate, and is it legal?
I'm not a lawyer.
I've told the people on the fourth floor I won't practice law.
But you came from political science.
Oh, yes.
So, opinions, you know, everybody's got one.
The city does have an option, which some believe is unconstitutional, about enforcing private deed restrictions.
Uh, and that's... Alec Bixley believes it's unconstitutional.
Well, I do too, but I'm not a judge, so I don't matter.
But anyway... Has there ever been a court test?
No, not up the line.
Why not?
I think they just go in and let them do it.
Just let them break the deed, especially.
Or they put so much pressure on them, politically and other ways.
You know, I'm not that familiar with that situation, but I do know that...
The deed restriction argument is fine as long as your subdivision has the goddamn restrictions.
Well, most of our growth took place in the 50s, so we're running out of those deed restrictions.
They last for how long?
Well, generally, 20 years.
It depends on the deal.
We don't have any say in what goes into these restrictions, by the way.
We can enforce them by a little special deal in the legislature, which, again, has not really been tested.
I'm not sure anybody would.
And it already applies to Houston, doesn't it?
Yes, it does.
It's a bracket that's one-five bill.
Large cities on a 20-mile-long stream named after a four-footed, very almost extinct quadruped.
But now we're finding that as more of these restrictions lapse, some of the more affluent citizens of our city
are confronted with the idea of stop and go's, you know, modeling studios in their neighborhoods.
And they don't like the work of God damn.
And it was okay if people in Montrose had to deal with it, or people in Third Ward.
But now it's moving down into Tanglewood and people are getting uppity.
You know, and we've got...
It's coming home to roost.
Yeah.
We've got people in the medical center area that want a very restrictive parking ordinance.
on some kinds of commercial property, a la San Francisco.
Well, you can't say some kinds of commercial property are going to have to provide off-street parking.
That's zoning.
You can't do that.
And we've told them it's illegal.
They want to do it anyway.
And the thing about that is, in their rush to do that, what they do is eliminate all the shops and stuff in some of these neighborhoods that really make the neighborhood.
And what you'll do is a guy will buy the house next to him, family evict, build a parking lot.
You've screwed up the economics of the whole goddamn neighborhood.
But there are things that are happening in a city that are moving toward growth management or zoning type remedies, such as the sign ordinance that was recently passed.
And there are some people on council that want more government intervention into the land use decisions.
which is ultimately, I think, as we discussed, probably the solution to our transportation woes rather than building trains and freeways.

It's basically some language decisions about where people do live and where they do work, and then you build those bridges with the transportation network, not build a network that serves everybody in the damn world.
Well, Houston is a city in trouble.
I wouldn't say that.
Well, okay.
We're a city in trouble with a AAA bond writing out.
Just let me remind you of that.
Well, not everything can be equated to the dollar sign.
Okay.
What money isn't, it can buy, but that's okay.
Everyone has his price.
That's right.
So I've been told.
Are you suggesting that I've just found mine?
No, would I do that?
You would.
How dare you?
Anyway, aside from the frivolity, Houston grew up at the wrong time, as it were.
All the eastern seaboard cities had their mass transit

facilities in place because they grew up before the advent of the automobile, and even the cities on the West Coast did the same, such as Los Angeles, of all creatures, with the red car system that operated beautifully up to and through the Second World War, at which time it was bought out by the automobile manufacturers in Detroit for clear reasons, and the rights-of-way no longer operative.
But anyway, what I'm saying is, now you mentioned energy as being one of your concerns.
And you mentioned the growth of Houston.
And you mentioned all the industries coming in.
And the mayor is very proud of the fact that Houston's economy is probably one of the brightest, if not the brightest spots for capital in the entire United States.
How do you relate all these together, Rick?

in terms of continuing to provide basic accessibility to various sites for various activities throughout the greater Houston area, given an energy crunch in the future, given a growing industrial base for Houston, given, therefore, the multiplier effect on the entire
retailing economy and business economy, wholesaling, distribution activities, and all the rest, and what the consequences are for residential activity and continued growth.
In terms of growth management, otherwise called planners by those of us who still identify ourselves as planners, how would you like to respond to, I guess this is a question,
I was hoping it was going to be rhetorical.
No, not at all.
Oh, Lord.
Would you like to handle that?
Yeah, I'll give it a shot.
I think that we're finding in Houston just recently a bit of an implosion, if you will, or at least some...
